Bellabeat Introduction

Urška Sršen is Bellabeat’s co-founder and Chief Creative Officer. Sando Mur is a Mathematician and Bellabeat’s co-founder, the key member of the Bellabeat executive team. Bellabeat, a high-tech company that manufactures health-focused smart products for women. Bellabeat is a successful small company; collecting data on activity, sleep, stress, and reproductive health has allowed Bellabeat to empower women with knowledge about their health and habits. Since it started in 2013, Bellabeat has grown rapidly and quickly positioned itself as a tech-driven wellness company for women.

Business Task

This report aims to analyze smart device usage data to gain insight into consumers’ use of non-Bellabeat smart devices. Then I would apply these insights to one of the Bellabeat products in my analysis.

Analysis Questions

  • 1.What are some trends in smart device usage?
  • 2.How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?
  • 3.How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

Notes: In this analysis, I collected two datasets to analyze and gain insight into consumers’ usage of these smart devices. The first dataset is called FitBit Fitness Tracker Data, and the second dataset is called Sleep Pattern.

Loading the Data

The first dataset is Fitbit Fitness Tracker Data has 18 CSV files. I’m focusing on loading daily_activity to analyze it. The second dataset is Sleep Pattern which has 1 CSV file called sleep_analysis to compare with the information I downloaded from the first dataset.

daily_activity <- read.csv("daily_activity.csv")

Once the dataframe file is uploaded, I’ll clean the CSV columns to make it easier for this data analysis process.

daily_activity <- daily_activity %>% 
  janitor::clean_names()

Now I’ll load the second dataset below as a dataframe:

sleep_analysis <- read.csv("sleep_analysis.csv")

Data Analysis

The daily_activity dataframe has total_steps and total_distance. I’ll create a new dataframe including total active minutes to compare with sedentary_minutes, total_steps, and total_distance.

daily_activity2 <- daily_activity %>% 
  select(id,
         total_steps,
         total_distance,
         very_active_minutes,
         lightly_active_minutes,
         fairly_active_minutes,
         sedentary_minutes) %>% 
  mutate(total_activemins = very_active_minutes + lightly_active_minutes +
           fairly_active_minutes)

As I did the summary above for daily_activity, then I’ll execute a summary for daily_activity2 below:

daily_activity2 %>% 
  select(total_steps,
         total_steps,
         total_distance,
         very_active_minutes,
         lightly_active_minutes,
         fairly_active_minutes,
         sedentary_minutes,

This dataframe is plotted using ggplot2 and illustrates the total of steps vs. total_activemins.

This visual reveals that users are usually active between 2.5 hours to 5.8 hours, and the incremental steps are between 0 to 20,000 a day. Bellabeat should market the application to improve upon the users increasing active hours a day or consistently staying in the same range.

ggplot(data = daily_activity2)+ 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = total_steps, y = total_activemins, color = total_distance )) +
  labs(title = "FitBit Fitness Tracker Total Steps vs.Total Active Mintues", caption = "Data collected from Möbius")

What’s the relationship between total_activemins taken in a day and sedentary_minutes?

It shows from 17 hours to 25 hours sedentary_mintues and 3.3 hours to 8.3 hours of total_activemins of a linear decline. There is also a cluster of points positioned at 13 hours of sedentary_minutes and 5 hours of total_activemins.

ggplot(data = daily_activity2) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = sedentary_minutes, y =total_activemins, color = total_steps))+
  labs(title = "FitBit Fitness Tracker Total Active Minutes vs. Sedentary Minutes", caption = "Data collected from Möbius")

What’s the relationship between screen_time and sleep_time in a day? Would there be any unexpected trends?

This unexpected trend in this graphic shows males start with fewer hours spent on a smart device, then gradually increased then decreased again. Females have a steady line then increased screen_time to 5 hours a day. The visual gives insight that females are usually sleeping around 7 hours a day. This information provides the marketing team with ways to improve the application that tracks the user sleep patterns.

Even though the company’s health-focused products market to females, the marketing team can propose a campaign to consider in the future to branch out and market the males.

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Let’s look at the relationship between the exercise vs. screen_time.

By default, users say yes to exercising when the average screen_time is 4 hours. However, screen_time has an increase of sometimes exercising when using a device of 5 hours.

ggplot(data = sleep_analysis)+
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = screen_time, fill = exercise))+
  labs(title = "Sleep Pattern Screen Time vs. Exercise", caption = "Data collected from Krupa Gajjar")

Let’s check the connection between meals_day, screen_time, and exercise. The visual wrap exercises data and gives an insight into how many meals_day and screen_time a user does in a day.

Bellabeat strategy should focus on marketing their Bellabeat app that provides users with health data related to their activity, sleep, stress, menstrual cycle, and mindfulness habits. This marketing strategy will help users track their meals a day, exercise, and monitor the time spent on their phones to make healthy decisions.

ggplot(data = sleep_analysis)+
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = screen_time, fill = meals_day))+ facet_wrap(~exercise)

  labs(title = "Sleep Pattern Screen Time vs. Meals Day", 
       caption = "Data collected from Krupa Gajjar")

Summary of my analysis

The FitBit Fitness Tracker and Sleep Pattern reveal users are sometimes active and have an increase in screen time. The data also shows users, on average, sleep about 6 hours, and the Bellabeat app would provide health data for users’ needs of their sleeping patterns. The recommended sleep time is 7 hours per day, and tracking sleeping patterns would benefit the consumer.

The company should take these insights and trends and use the findings to promote the Bellabeat app since the data shows users are using their smart devices on average 4 hours a day. With users being active 4 hours a day and sedentary for 17 hours, the company should advertise features that focus more on the user to increase their daily routine in being more mindful of working out more than being inactive.

This project gathered the daily_activity dataset from FitBit Fitness Tracker and the sleep_analysis dataset from Sleep Pattern. I will continue to analyze other datasets from FitBit Fitness Tracker to retrieve more insights of users using non-Bellabeat smart devices.

I’m open to receiving feedback on my analysis. Thank you.
